Note:
This file handles process management and process operations wrapper functionality for the Runa runtime system interface.

This file provides the subprocess primitives that back the compile-and-run
driver ("runa run"): the fork/execve/wait4 trio plus the high-level run and
spawn entry points. All syscalls go through the platform-agnostic system_call
gateway and the SYS_* router accessors so the same source compiles for every
supported POSIX target without hardcoded syscall numbers.

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- process_fork: raw fork that returns 0 in the child, child-pid in the parent
- process_execve: replace the current image with a new program
- process_wait: block on a child pid and decode its exit status
- process_run: fork + exec + wait, returning the child's exit code
- process_spawn: fork + exec, returning the child's pid without waiting
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/syscall.runa" as Syscall
Import "runtime/integration/system_interface/syscall_manager.runa" as SyscallMgr
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory

Process called "process_fork" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    process_fork is the lowest-level primitive in this module: it duplicates the
    calling process via the platform fork syscall. The kernel returns the value
    twice along two control paths — 0 to the freshly created child and the
    child's pid to the parent — which is exactly the contract callers rely on to
    branch between "I am the child" and "I am the parent". A negative return
    signals that the kernel could not create the process (resource limits, out of
    memory) and is propagated unchanged so callers can react.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    fork takes no arguments, so every argument register is passed as 0. The
    syscall number is resolved through the SYS_FORK router accessor, which selects
    the correct per-platform constant at compile time, and dispatched through the
    common system_call gateway (which routes to syscall_6 on the host). The raw
    kernel return value is returned verbatim: 0 in the child, child-pid in the
    parent, negative errno-encoded value on failure.
    @End Implementation
    Let fork_num be proc SYS_FORK from Syscall
    Return proc system_call from SyscallMgr with fork_num, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0
End Process

Process called "process_execve" takes path_cstr as Integer, argv as Integer, envp as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    process_execve replaces the current process image with the program named by
    path_cstr, using argv as the argument vector and envp as the environment
    vector. On success the call NEVER returns — control transfers into the new
    program — so any value this Process actually returns is by definition a
    failure indication (a negative errno-encoded value). Callers in the child
    branch of a fork therefore treat "execve returned at all" as "exec failed".
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    The three pointer arguments are already-marshalled C arrays supplied by the
    caller: path_cstr is a NUL-terminated byte string, argv is a heap block of
    8-byte C-string pointers terminated by a 0 entry, and envp has the same shape
    (a pointer to a single 0 for an empty environment). They are passed straight
    through as a1/a2/a3 with the remaining argument registers zeroed. The syscall
    number is resolved via the SYS_EXECVE router accessor. Because execve must not
    allocate or touch shared Runa heap state in the post-fork child, this Process
    performs no allocation of its own — it is a pure syscall pass-through.
    @End Implementation
    Let execve_num be proc SYS_EXECVE from Syscall
    Return proc system_call from SyscallMgr with execve_num, path_cstr, argv, envp, 0, 0, 0
End Process

Process called "process_wait" takes pid as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    process_wait blocks the parent until the child identified by pid terminates,
    then decodes the kernel's packed wait status into a conventional exit code.
    The raw status word encodes two distinct termination modes — normal exit and
    death by signal — and callers want a single integer that mirrors a shell's
    $? convention, so this Process performs that decode rather than exposing the
    raw word.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    A small 8-byte status buffer is allocated on the owned heap to receive the
    wait status (the kernel writes a 32-bit int; 8 bytes covers it with room to
    spare and matches pointer-sized allocations). wait4 is invoked as
    system_call(SYS_WAIT4, pid, status_buf, 0 options, 0 rusage, 0, 0). The status
    int is read back with memory_get_integer.

    Status decode follows the standard POSIX macros:
    - WIFEXITED is true when (status bit_and 127) is equal to 0 (no signal in the
      low 7 bits). In that case the exit code is (status shifted right by 8)
      bit_and 255 — the WEXITSTATUS byte.
    - Otherwise the child was killed by a signal; we return 128 plus the signal
      number (status bit_and 127), matching shell convention for signal deaths.

    The status buffer is always freed before returning so no allocation leaks
    across the wait. (Runa precedence makes "shifted right by" weaker than
    bit_and, so the WEXITSTATUS expression is parenthesized to force the shift
    before the mask.)
    @End Implementation
    Let wait_num be proc SYS_WAIT4 from Syscall
    Let status_buf be proc allocate from Layout with 8
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with status_buf, 0, 0
    Let wait_result be proc system_call from SyscallMgr with wait_num, pid, status_buf, 0, 0, 0, 0
    Let status be proc memory_get_integer from Memory with status_buf, 0
    proc deallocate from Layout with status_buf
    Let signal_bits be status bit_and 127
    If signal_bits is equal to 0:
        Let shifted be status shifted right by 8
        Return shifted bit_and 255
    End If
    Return 128 plus signal_bits
End Process

Process called "process_run" takes path_cstr as Integer, argv as Integer, envp as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    process_run is the high-level synchronous entry point for "runa run": it
    forks a child, executes the requested program in that child, waits for it to
    finish, and returns its exit code. This is the building block a compile-and-run
    driver needs to launch the freshly built binary and surface its status to the
    user.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    FORK-SAFETY CONTRACT (critical): the caller marshals path_cstr / argv / envp
    BEFORE invoking this Process — they are already-built C arrays (argv and envp
    are heap blocks of 8-byte C-string pointers terminated by a 0 entry; path_cstr
    is NUL-terminated bytes; envp may point at a single 0 for an empty
    environment). Between the fork return and the execve, the child path does
    NOTHING that allocates, prints, or mutates shared Runa heap state — it calls
    only process_execve and, if that returns (meaning exec failed), terminates
    immediately with the RAW SYS_EXIT syscall using code 127. We deliberately use
    the raw kernel _exit-style syscall rather than any Runa exit that would run
    finalizers, because finalizers running in a half-forked child would corrupt
    shared heap state. 127 is the conventional "command not found / exec failed"
    code.

    Control flow:
    - pid < 0: fork failed, return -1.
    - pid == 0: we are the child. Attempt exec; if it returns, raw-exit 127.
    - pid > 0: we are the parent. Wait on the child and return its decoded exit
      code.
    @End Implementation
    Let pid be process_fork
    If pid is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If pid is equal to 0:
        Let exec_failed be process_execve with path_cstr, argv, envp
        Let exit_num be proc SYS_EXIT from Syscall
        proc system_call from SyscallMgr with exit_num, 127, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0
        Return 127
    End If
    Return process_wait with pid
End Process

Process called "process_spawn" takes path_cstr as Integer, argv as Integer, envp as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    process_spawn is the asynchronous counterpart to process_run: it forks and
    execs the requested program but returns the child's pid to the parent WITHOUT
    waiting. This lets callers launch background work and later reap it with
    process_wait at a time of their choosing.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    The same FORK-SAFETY CONTRACT as process_run applies: path_cstr / argv / envp
    are pre-marshalled C arrays, and the post-fork child path performs no
    allocation, printing, or shared-heap mutation before execve. On exec failure
    the child terminates immediately with the raw SYS_EXIT syscall and code 127
    (no finalizers run in the child).

    Control flow:
    - pid < 0: fork failed, return -1.
    - pid == 0: we are the child. Attempt exec; if it returns, raw-exit 127.
    - pid > 0: we are the parent. Return the child's pid immediately, without
      waiting.
    @End Implementation
    Let pid be process_fork
    If pid is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If pid is equal to 0:
        Let exec_failed be process_execve with path_cstr, argv, envp
        Let exit_num be proc SYS_EXIT from Syscall
        proc system_call from SyscallMgr with exit_num, 127, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0
        Return 127
    End If
    Return pid
End Process
